      <h1>Indicators in Pine Script</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Full explanation of indicators in Pine Script with a walk-through of a Stochastic Indicator in Pine Script.</p>
      <div class="byline">Sanhith Vandara · Oct 9, 2025</div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>What Is an Indicator?</h2>
    <p>An indicator is a tool used in technical analysis to help analysts understand market trends, price movements, and potential buy/sell options.</p>
    <p>On TradingView, Pine Script allows you to program custom indicators to help analyze chart and price data. They are plotted on charts for a visual representation.</p>

    <div class="screenshot">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="TradingView chart showing a MACD (Basic) indicator plotted below the price action">
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Well… What Do They Do?</h2>
    <p>Indicators can do many different things with the data on the chart. Some of their functions include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Measuring trends</li>
      <li>Measuring momentum</li>
      <li>Understanding volatility and price fluctuations</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Types of Indicators</h2>
    <p>There are different types of indicators in technical analysis, as well as a couple of main classifications:</p>

    <div class="indicator-card">
      <h4>Trend Indicators</h4>
      <p>Helps identify the direction of a market (uptrend / downtrend).</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Moving Averages (SMA, EMA, RMA…)</li>
        <li>Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)*</li>
        <li>Parabolic Stop and Reverse</li>
        <li>Ichimoku Cloud</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="indicator-card">
      <h4>Momentum Oscillators</h4>
      <p>Measures momentum, or the speed and strength of price movements.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Relative Strength Index (RSI)</li>
        <li>Stochastic Oscillator</li>
        <li>Momentum Indicator</li>
        <li>Rate of Change (RoC)</li>
        <li>Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)*</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="indicator-card">
      <h4>Volatility Indicators</h4>
      <p>Measure volatility — how much and how quickly an asset's price changes over a period of time. Great for understanding risk and how "active" the market is.</p>
      <p><strong>High Volatility:</strong> prices are making bigger moves with frequent change in price.<br>
      <strong>Low Volatility:</strong> prices are more steady and stay in a lower range.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Bollinger Bands (BB)</li>
        <li>Average True Range (ATR)</li>
        <li>Standard Deviation Indicator</li>
        <li>Volatility Index</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>There are hundreds, if not thousands, of other indicators in technical analysis. In addition, you can have multi-indicator scripts in TradingView — for example, combining RSI, MACD, and more in a single script.</p>
    <p>Indicators are your tools, and choosing the right tool can greatly benefit you if you are trading. Tracking patterns such as trends, reversals, breakouts, and more can be done with indicators.</p>

    <div class="footnote">
      * The Moving Average Convergence Divergence, also known as MACD, is both a trend and a momentum indicator.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Example of an Indicator in Pine Script</h2>
    <p>This indicator is the <strong>Stochastic Oscillator</strong>, a type of momentum oscillator. It compares an asset's closing price to its price range over a period of time. It helps analysts identify overbought and oversold market conditions.</p>

    <p>The formula is:</p>
    <div class="formula-image">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Stochastic Oscillator formula: percent K equals (Close minus Lowest Low) divided by (Highest High minus Lowest Low), times 100">
    </div>
    <p class="formula-caption">%K = main signal line</p>

    <div class="code-label">Pine Script — Stochastic Oscillator</div>
    <pre><span class="func">indicator</span>(<span class="string">"Stochastic Oscillator"</span>)

length = input.int(<span class="num">14</span>, title = <span class="string">"Length"</span>)
smooth = input.int(<span class="num">3</span>, title = <span class="string">"Smooth"</span>)

<span class="comment">// Formula calculations</span>
lowest_low = ta.lowest(low, length)
highest_high = ta.highest(high, length)
k = <span class="num">100</span> * (close - lowest_low) / (highest_high - lowest_low)
k_smooth = ta.sma(k, smooth)

<span class="comment">// plotting</span>
<span class="func">plot</span>(k_smooth, color = color.blue, title = <span class="string">"%K Line"</span>, linewidth = <span class="num">2</span>)
<span class="func">hline</span>(<span class="num">80</span>, <span class="string">"Overbought"</span>, color = color.red)
<span class="func">hline</span>(<span class="num">20</span>, <span class="string">"Oversold"</span>, color = color.green)</pre>

    <p>Here is the Simple Stochastic Indicator on the chart:</p>
    <div class="screenshot">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="TradingView chart of Texas Instruments with a Simple Stochastic indicator plotted below price, oscillating between overbought and oversold levels">
    </div>

    <p>And the indicator in the Pine Editor:</p>
    <div class="screenshot">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Pine Editor showing the full Stochastic Oscillator script with syntax highlighting">
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Breakdown of the Program</h2>
    <pre><span class="comment">// declare indicator</span>
<span class="func">indicator</span>(<span class="string">"Stochastic Oscillator"</span>)

<span class="comment">// number of bars used to calculate high-low range</span>
length = input.int(<span class="num">14</span>, title = <span class="string">"Length"</span>)

<span class="comment">// number of periods used to 'smooth' the %K line with a moving average</span>
smooth = input.int(<span class="num">3</span>, title = <span class="string">"Smooth"</span>)

<span class="comment">// Formula calculations</span>

<span class="comment">// find the lowest low price</span>
lowest_low = ta.lowest(low, length)

<span class="comment">// find the highest high over the last 'length' bars</span>
highest_high = ta.highest(high, length)

<span class="comment">// these form the price range used in the next step</span>

<span class="comment">// stochastic formula</span>
k = <span class="num">100</span> * (close - lowest_low) / (highest_high - lowest_low)

<span class="comment">// apply a simple moving average (SMA)</span>
k_smooth = ta.sma(k, smooth)

<span class="comment">// plotting the indicator</span>
<span class="func">plot</span>(k_smooth, color = color.blue, title = <span class="string">"%K Line"</span>, linewidth = <span class="num">2</span>)

<span class="comment">/* reference lines
   &gt; 80 - potential overbought zone
   &lt; 20 - potential oversold zone */</span>
<span class="func">hline</span>(<span class="num">80</span>, <span class="string">"Overbought"</span>, color = color.red)
<span class="func">hline</span>(<span class="num">20</span>, <span class="string">"Oversold"</span>, color = color.green)</pre>
  </section>

